var _markdown = "\n\nRustFS is a high-performance, distributed object storage system written in Rust, fully compatible with the S3 protocol and released under the Apache 2.0 license. It combines simplicity with efficiency to deliver an open-source, commercially-friendly object storage solution suitable for private cloud, data lake, AI/ML, and cloud-native workloads.\n\n## Get Started [#get-started]\n\n* [Installation Guide](/installation/) — deploy RustFS on Linux, Windows, macOS, or Docker.\n* [Quick Start on Linux](/installation/linux/quick-start) — one-click installation package.\n* [What is RustFS?](/concepts/introduction) — architecture, features, and design principles.\n\n## Explore [#explore]\n\n* [Manage RustFS](/management/bucket/) — buckets and objects.\n* [Developer Guide](/developer/) — MCP, MinIO Client, and SDKs.\n* [Product Features](/features/distributed/) — distributed architecture, versioning, encryption, and more.\n* [Solutions](/features/data-lake/) — data lake, AI/ML, cloud-native, and industry use cases.\n\n## Key Features [#key-features]\n\n* **S3 Compatible** — seamless integration with the S3 ecosystem.\n* **Distributed Architecture** — scales horizontally across nodes and disks.\n* **High Performance** — Rust performance with modern memory-safety guarantees.\n* **Enterprise-Ready** — Apache 2.0 licensed, safe for commercial integration.\n* **Cloud-Native** — optimized for Docker and Kubernetes.\n";
